9845315478742123, 0.02053801901638508, -0.018140802159905434, 0.022043248638510704, 0.028543608263134956, 0.003947046119719744, -0.005577710922807455, -0.0038717843126505613, 0.03773108124732971, -0.0323791578412056, 0.012632776983082294, 0.021574953570961952, -0.004696873016655445, 0.008613256737589836, -0.04047394543886185, -0.0058313701301813126, -0.03255755454301834, 0.002752618631348014, 0.016011180356144905, 0.003119169734418392, -0.012064134702086449, 0.00639443751424551, -0.01203068532049656, -0.028967302292585373, 0.03148716688156128, 0.009616742841899395, -0.00818956270813942, 0.032735951244831085, -0.007236250676214695, 0.015241840854287148, 0.018586795777082443, 0.04145513102412224, 0.006232764571905136, 0.0007491303840652108, 0.03014918603003025, 0.002437635324895382]], "input": ["\"SLACK\":\"Slack is the difference between maximum resources available and resources used at the optimal point in linear programming problems. For binding constraints, the value of slack is zero.\"", "\"NON-BINDING AND BINDING CONSTRAINTS\":\"In linear programming, non-binding constraints are those where not all of the available supply of one or more inputs is used at the optimal point, while binding constraints are fully utilized.\"", "\"IMPLICATIONS OF SLACK\":\"Knowing the amount of slack is useful for planning additional supplies of resources or utilizing excess resources elsewhere in the business.\"", "\"MORE THAN TWO VARIABLES\":\"Linear programming can be formulated for any number of variables and constraints, but graphical methods are limited to two variables. Methods for more than two variables include the dual problem and simplex.\"", "\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING SUMMARY\":\"Summary of linear programming steps: define variables, define the objective function, formulate constraints, plot constraints, identify the feasible area, find the optimal point, and calculate maximum profit.\"", "\"PRICING DECISIONS\":\"Pricing decisions involve factors influencing product pricing, price elasticity of demand, demand equations, optimum selling price, and various pricing strategies.\"", "\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Full cost plus pricing\" is a long-term pricing strategy that ensures prices cover all variable and fixed costs. The price of a product using full cost plus pricing is calculated by adding a markup to the full cost per unit.", "\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING FORMULA\":\"Selling price per unit = (Total budgeted production cost + Total budgeted non-production cost + Mark-up) / Budgeted sales units\"", "\"ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Advantages of full cost plus pricing include: profit will be made if the budget sales level is achieved, the full cost should be readily available if a system of standard costing is in operation, it is appropriate where fixed costs are significant, useful for justifying prices and price rises, and it is simple and cheap to operate.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Disadvantages of full cost plus pricing include: the method of accounting for overheads will have a large impact on the costs calculated for different products, losses may occur if actual sales are below budget, it ignores external factors like demand/price relationship and competitors' prices, the size of the mark-up is arbitrary, and it may not maximize profits.\"", "\"MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Marginal cost plus pricing is a short-term pricing strategy that involves calculating the selling price per unit by adding a mark-up percentage to the budgeted variable production and non-production costs.\"", "\"MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING FORMULA\":\"Selling price per unit = (Budgeted Variable production cost + Budgeted Variable non-production cost + Mark-up) / Budgeted sales units\"", "\"ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Advantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: the mark-up represents contribution, which is useful in short-term pricing decisions like market penetration policy, and it treats fixed costs by their nature and not using an arbitrary allocation.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\":\"Disadvantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: it may lead to failure to recover fixed costs, and it is not appropriate for long-term pricing, particularly where fixed costs are significant, because in the long-term, fixed costs may also vary and not be sufficiently covered by mark-up.\"", "\"RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI) PRICING\":\"ROI pricing is a long-term pricing method where prices are set to achieve a target percentage return on the capital invested in production.\"", "\"ROI PRICING FORMULA\":\"Selling price per unit = Budgeted full cost + (target ROI percentage x capital employed) / Budgeted sales units\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}